## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

Your code has two patterns:

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| **Timeout enforcement** | `thread.Abort()` after `Join(timeout)` fails | `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` |
| **ThreadAbortException as control flow** | `catch (ThreadAbortException) { Thread.ResetAbort(); }` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |

### Why It Breaks

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+. `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone. There is no way to forcibly terminate a managed thread — you **must** switch to cooperative cancellation.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerException is OperationCanceledException
                                             && cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### What Changed and Why

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(...)` | Tasks use the thread pool; no manual thread lifecycle |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` + `thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource(timeout)` | Token auto-cancels after the deadline |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException) { ResetAbort(); }` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | Cooperative cancellation throws `OperationCanceledException` |
| `Func<T> work` | `Func<CancellationToken, T> work` | Work **must** receive and check the token |

### Callers Must Change

The `work` delegate now receives a `CancellationToken` and **must cooperate**:

```csharp
// Before (.NET Framework) — work is oblivious to cancellation
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => ExpensiveCalculation(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// After (.NET 8) — work checks the token
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct =>
    {
        foreach (var item in items)
        {
            ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
            Process(item);
        }
        return ComputeFinal();
    },
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

---

### Key Pitfalls

1. **Cancellation is not immediate.** Unlike `Thread.Abort` which injected an exception at any point, cooperative cancellation only fires at checkpoints. Insert `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside loops and between expensive steps.

2. **Forgetting to pass the token through the call chain.** If `work` calls other methods, pass `ct` all the way down. One method that ignores the token blocks the entire cancellation.

3. **Blocking calls won't respond to the token.** Replace `Thread.Sleep(ms)` with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)`. Use async I/O overloads that accept `CancellationToken`.

4. **Dispose the `CancellationTokenSource`.** It holds timer resources when created with a timeout. The `using` statement handles this.

5. **Uncooperative code (can't modify the work).** If you truly can't add token checks (e.g., third-party library), move the work to a **child process** and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout. There is no in-process equivalent of `Thread.Abort` in modern .NET.
